Researchers at different institutions in Tokyo, noted that rats flatten their ears, narrow their eyes and puff up their cheeks when they are in pain .
They found that rats flattened their ears and narrow their faces when they were in pain - an observation observed in previous studies .
The scientists said rats were ‘naive’ in the study and that they may even use expressions to warn other rats of danger or ask for help .
This could shed light on autism and other conditions that involve difficulties in communication .